        <Parent_Subject_ID>300265621</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>inkjet prints [300265621], digital prints [300312222], prints by process or technique [300041337], prints (visual works) [300041273], visual works by material or technique [300191091], visual works (works) [300191086], Visual Works (hierarchy name) [300179869], Visual and Verbal Communication (hierarchy name) [300264552], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Digital prints made with an ink jet process, originally used interchangeably with "Iris prints," but now more often used to refer to high-volume editions of reproductions rather than high-quality original art. The term "giclée" was coined by the printmaker Jack Duganne in 1991 to refer to inkjet prints on high-quality paper, but the usage is now evolving to become broader.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051049/Baldwin and Jürgens, Looking at Photographs (2009)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047782/Memorial Art Gallery (2002-2006)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Een afdruk die is gemaakt met de Iris, een grote inkjetprinter, die oorspronkelijk werd gebruikt voor drukproeven in de offset-lithografie en sinds de jaren 90 van de 20ste eeuw voor kunstdrukwerk, meestal fotografisch. Deze afdrukken kunnen op verschillende materialen worden gemaakt, zoals papier, canvas, en mylar.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bezieht sich auf einen Digitaldruck, der mit einem Tintenstrahldruckverfahren hergestellt wurde; ursprünglich wurde der Begriff synonym mit "Irisdruck" gebraucht, wird nun aber öfter in Bezug auf Massenauflagen von Reproduktionen verwendet als auf hochwertige Originalkunst. Der Begriff "Giclée" wurde von dem Graphiker Jack Duganne 1991 in Bezug auf Tintenstrahldrucke auf hochwertigem Papier geprägt, aber der Begriff wird nun umfassender verwendet.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指用噴墨工序製作的數位印刷，原本與「虹彩版畫(Iris prints)」一詞交替使用，但現在較常指大量的複製版本，而非高品質的原創藝術。「微噴」一詞乃版畫家傑克．杜加內（Jack Duganne）於西元1991年所創，指在高品質紙張上製作噴墨版畫，但現在其用法已變得更為廣泛。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
